00:14:27,367 --> 00:14:30,453
HEARTLESS, PASSIONLESS

135
00:14:35,458 --> 00:14:37,419
THROUGH MY FAULT

136
00:15:48,823 --> 00:15:51,076
Hello.

137
00:15:51,117 --> 00:15:53,411
I was in your class at university.

138
00:15:53,453 --> 00:15:55,038
Were you?

139
00:15:56,373 --> 00:15:58,291
Did they find someone to fill in?

140
00:15:58,333 --> 00:16:00,627
Yeah, a McGill student.

141
00:16:02,045 --> 00:16:03,296
Good.

142
00:16:04,089 --> 00:16:06,091
Are you here to sell some books?

143
00:16:06,132 --> 00:16:07,008
Yes.

144
00:16:09,928 --> 00:16:11,638
Put them there.

145
00:16:24,651 --> 00:16:27,153
We only accept French books.

146
00:16:28,738 --> 00:16:30,198
Of course.

147
00:16:38,081 --> 00:16:39,916
There are some real gems here.

148
00:16:39,958 --> 00:16:41,251
Yeah.

149
00:16:44,129 --> 00:16:46,256
What are you doing now?

150
00:16:47,006 --> 00:16:49,008
Translating.

151
00:16:49,801 --> 00:16:51,469
Translating what?

152
00:16:52,804 --> 00:16:55,348
Some poems by Edward Stachura.

153
00:16:55,390 --> 00:16:57,058
I've never heard of him.

154
00:16:57,308 --> 00:17:00,645
He had a huge youth following in Poland.

155
00:17:01,020 --> 00:17:03,940
He sold 100,000 copies of his poetry collections.

156
00:17:03,982 --> 00:17:06,067
He translated Gaston Miron.

157
00:17:06,985 --> 00:17:08,778
Is he still alive?

158
00:17:10,405 --> 00:17:12,490
He killed himself in 1979.

159
00:17:15,243 --> 00:17:17,662
So why are you selling your books?

160
00:17:17,704 --> 00:17:19,539
What's it to you?

161
00:17:20,498 --> 00:17:22,459
I'm just curious.

162
00:17:24,753 --> 00:17:27,213
I need the room.

163
00:17:38,933 --> 00:17:42,187
The barefoot in the streets of the world

164
00:17:42,687 --> 00:17:45,648
The naked in the streets of the world

165
00:17:46,691 --> 00:17:49,861
The hungry in the streets of the world

166
00:17:50,361 --> 00:17:52,197
Through my fault

167
00:17:52,489 --> 00:17:54,157
Through my fault

168
00:17:55,074 --> 00:17:57,118
Through my most grievous fault!

169
00:17:59,370 --> 00:18:02,290
Horror - there is no end to horror

170
00:18:03,082 --> 00:18:06,085
Crime - there is no end to crime

171
00:18:07,086 --> 00:18:10,215
War - there is no end to war

172
00:18:11,174 --> 00:18:12,801
Through my fault

173
00:18:13,134 --> 00:18:14,844
Through my fault

174
00:18:15,261 --> 00:18:17,430
Through my most grievous fault!

175
00:18:54,717 --> 00:18:56,344
Dad?

176
00:18:56,970 --> 00:18:59,389
I just wanted to see how you were doing.

177
00:19:46,561 --> 00:19:48,980
This was your great-grandfather's house.

178
00:19:49,022 --> 00:19:50,982
You've never talked about him.

179
00:19:52,275 --> 00:19:54,193
I was born here.

180
00:19:56,112 --> 00:19:58,239
We lived with my grandparents.

181
00:19:58,656 --> 00:20:00,575
The farm should've gone to my father,

182
00:20:00,617 --> 00:20:03,912
but there was a fight and my grandfather kicked us out.

183
00:20:03,953 --> 00:20:05,622
What was the fight about?

184
00:20:06,372 --> 00:20:08,333
I don't really know.

185
00:20:10,418 --> 00:20:14,172
They probably didn't agree on how to manage the land.

186
00:20:14,213 --> 00:20:16,299
My grandfather lost his temper.

187
00:20:18,092 --> 00:20:21,846
My father had worked for him for free for 10 years.

188
00:20:23,723 --> 00:20:26,184
There was nothing in writing.

189
00:20:26,893 --> 00:20:30,063
My parents lost everything overnight.

190
00:20:30,313 --> 00:20:33,024
They already had four children by then.

191
00:20:33,399 --> 00:20:36,778
We moved to Quebec City. Dad found work at the port.

192
00:20:36,819 --> 00:20:39,364
He refused to ever set foot here again.

193
00:20:40,990 --> 00:20:43,534
How old were you when you left?

194
00:20:43,576 --> 00:20:45,328
Five.

195
00:20:48,790 --> 00:20:51,709
When I heard the property was for sale, I bought it.

196
00:20:53,628 --> 00:20:55,546
Life's funny, isn't it?

197
00:21:01,094 --> 00:21:03,763
I got my lawyers to rezone the area.

198
00:21:04,389 --> 00:21:06,391
We're turning it into a resort,

199
00:21:06,432 --> 00:21:09,185
like the one on the other side of the river.

200
00:21:12,605 --> 00:21:16,609
We just have to clear a few trees.

201
00:21:17,360 --> 00:21:22,281
We'll have a great view of the St. Lawrence and the islands.

202
00:21:24,450 --> 00:21:27,078
Why a vacation community?

203
00:21:27,328 --> 00:21:31,165
We'll build about 50 cottages, scattered throughout the woods.

204
00:21:31,207 --> 00:21:33,292
Not too close together.

205
00:21:33,793 --> 00:21:36,504
And we'll keep as many trees as we can.

206
00:21:37,255 --> 00:21:40,466
There'll be a community centre where the farm buildings are,

207
00:21:40,508 --> 00:21:45,430
with a convenience store, a hall and a few guest rooms.

208
00:21:46,431 --> 00:21:49,434
We'll keep the old exteriors intact,

209
00:21:49,475 --> 00:21:51,102
wherever possible.

210
00:21:56,441 --> 00:21:59,527
You never considered leaving it the way it was?

211
00:22:00,445 --> 00:22:04,240
A piece of land like this? An hour and half away from the city?

212
00:22:04,282 --> 00:22:07,118
If I don't do it, someone else will.

213
00:22:11,372 --> 00:22:16,127
Anyway, when it's yours, you can do what you want with it.

214
00:22:16,169 --> 00:22:18,337
I told you I won't take it.

215
00:22:22,050 --> 00:22:24,719
It would be a nice place to write though.

216
00:22:24,761 --> 00:22:27,346
You'd feel right at home in that little house.

217
00:22:33,311 --> 00:22:36,522
My will is with Dutil & Associates on Grande-Allée.

218
00:22:36,564 --> 00:22:38,733
Let it go, Dad.

219
00:22:40,818 --> 00:22:42,820
It's a done deal.

220
00:22:43,696 --> 00:22:45,907
There's nothing you can do about it.

221
00:22:46,949 --> 00:22:48,701
You're my son.

222
00:22:49,452 --> 00:22:51,412
It belongs to you.

